{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017QVCnh93dn5JrvKFVpcxp6","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the setup. The CockroachDB cluster is running in insecure mode. I need to:\n\n1. Generate TLS certificates using the openssl-toolbox pod\n2. Create Kubernetes secrets with those certificates\n3. Update the StatefulSet to use TLS instead of insecure mode\n\nThe CockroachDB TLS setup requires:\n- A CA certificate and key\n- A node certificate and key (for each node)\n- A client certificate and key (for the root user)\n\nThe certificates need to be placed in `/cockroach/cockroach-certs/` on each pod.\nI'll need to generate the CA and certificates, bundle them into Kubernetes secrets, then modify the StatefulSet to mount those secrets and switch from `--insecure` to `--certs-dir=/cockroach/cockroach-certs`, plus update the health checks to use HTTPS instead. CockroachDB has its own certificate generation commands built in, so I can use those instead of openssl. I'll check if the cockroach binary is available in one of the pods and use `cockroach cert create-ca`, `cockroach cert create-node`, and `cockroach cert create-client` to generate the necessary certificates. create Kubernetes secrets from those certs, then update the StatefulSet to mount them and switch from insecure mode to using the certs directory. I need to include SANs for all the node hostnames and service DNS names to ensure the certificates are valid across the cluster. Completing the node certificate with all the cluster endpoints, then creating a root client certificate, and finally packaging everything into a Kubernetes secret to use with the StatefulSet.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1930,"cache_read_input_tokens":29312,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1930},"output_toke